<subSubSection id="93E21162C9300D7580E2D78462A99FD3" pageId="33" pageNumber="34" type="specimens examined">
<paragraph id="A73DF97D0E6FC7FABFAD7FBA52153167" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">Specimens examined.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="526BD87EED5BD5E76C6141A813033D46" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">
Mexico. 
<emphasis id="66A53B908220D06A97F5C84AB50F94C8" bold="true" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">Durango:</emphasis>
Transect from Paseo de Cerro Gordo to the top (cumbre), 
<geoCoordinate id="4D48D24636C98B15B2FDDE8A13460227" degrees="23" direction="north" minutes="12" orientation="latitude" precision="1" seconds="31.1" value="23.20864">23°12'31.1&quot;N</geoCoordinate>
, 
<geoCoordinate id="6E10B43E2ADFB059B7B4D70506C59882" degrees="104" direction="west" minutes="56" orientation="longitude" precision="1" seconds="53.0" value="-104.94806">104°56'53.0&quot;W</geoCoordinate>
, 3136-3348 m, 9 Sep 2006, P.M.Peterson 20011 &amp; F.
<normalizedToken id="F382CD0836305ECD0A2B0AC6AC0E4F5C" originalValue="Sánchez-Alvarado">Sanchez-Alvarado</normalizedToken>
(CIIDIR, US).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="3B2A80570347A9A2C14AA1EFBB6C7B1C" pageId="33" pageNumber="34" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="3132A9CADFA945E87229CF5C878065F7" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">Discussion.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="04B7EE0B024DBFF7FB3094D66FE31FFC" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">Cerro Gordo is quite remote from other high peaks in the area as it takes nearly 10 hours of driving from Durango along a dirt road to reach the base of the mountain, just south of Maiz Gordo. There are other mountains in Durango that approach this height and it would seem reasonable to assume that this species might occur on these.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
